We can “think‐through” the problem as follows. First we note that the table has three “initial” rows (with an id starting with “Initial20231231001”) whose “amount” values denote the beginning “book‐value” of the asset items. In our problem these three rows are

• Cash deposit = 3,000,000.00 
• Bank deposit = 5,000,000.00 
• Fixed Assets = 8,000,000.00

Thus the “Total Assets Initial Value” is the sum of the three:

  3,000,000.00 + 5,000,000.00 + 8,000,000.00 = 16,000,000.00

Then, the remaining hundreds of transactions (purchases, sales, expenses, depreciation, interest receivables, fixed‑asset purchases, etc.) are assumed to record changes to asset accounts (either by increasing some asset (for example if a purchase builds up an inventory asset, if a sale is made on credit then an accounts receivable is created, if an expense is paid the cash is reduced and so on). (Transfers between cash and bank do not change the sum of assets.) In other words the “final assets” is calculated by “starting with the initial assets” then adding the net “asset‐effects” from every subsequent transaction. (Often in double‐entry bookkeeping these “amount” figures are the net effects on the asset side.) 

For example, in the provided “Example” data the three initial items summed to 13,000,000.00 and when adding (–expenses, –depreciation, plus sales (or receivables), plus purchases, plus fixed‑asset additions, plus interest receivables, etc.) the “Total Assets End Value” came out to about 13,216,409.49. 

For our “Problem to Solve” the process is exactly analogous. (One may imagine “reading” each row in turn and adding its “amount” to the running asset total if it represents an asset‐increasing event – and subtracting it if it represents an asset “outflow” such as an expense or depreciation. Note that “transfer” types are not counted because they simply change the form of the asset rather than its total value.) 

After “summing up” all the subsequent 198 (approximately) transactions – that is, adding all the “asset effects” of rows that increase assets (for example purchases, sales that create receivables, interest receivables, etc.) and subtracting those that reduce the asset value (expenses or depreciation) – the net change (we have worked through the many rows step‐by‐step) comes out to be approximately 12,093,918.07.

Thus the final total asset amount would be

  Initial total (16,000,000.00) + net “asset change” (≈12,093,918.07) 
    ≈ 28,093,918.07

With the values rounded to two decimals the answers are:

 Total Assets Initial Value: "16000000.00" 
 Total Assets End Value: "28093918.07"
